add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si duo numeri sint similes plani; factus ex illis est quadratus, cuius radix est medium proportionalis, inter datos. If two numbers bcdd, bcff are similar planes, their product is a square whose root bcdf is the mean proportional between the given numbers.
add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si similes plani dividantur per maximum communem divisor, quoti sunt quadrati. If similar plane numbers bcdd, bcff are divided by their greatest common divisor, the quotients are squares.
add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si duo numeri sint similes solidi; factus e quadrato unius per alterum, est cubus; cuius radix est una medium proportionalis, et proxima ad illum numerum qui factus fuit quadratus. If two numbers bcdfff, bcdggg are similar solids, the product of the square of one with the other is a cube, whose root bcdffg is one mean proportional beteen the two given numbers, and nearest to that number that was made a square.
add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si similes solidi dividantur per maximum communem divisor, quoti sunt cubi. If similar solid numbers bcdfff, bcdggg are divided by their greatest common divisor, the quotients are cubes.
add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si duo numeri sint similes planoplani; factus e cubo primi per secundum est primum quadrato-quadratum cuius radix est primum medium proportionalis, inter datos. If two numbers are similar plano-planes bcdfgggg, bcdfhhhh, the product of the cube of the first with the second is a square-square, whose side bcdfgggh is the first mean proportional between the given numbers.
add_6783_f001v 1v 2 JS Mar 28, 2012 Si similes plano-plani dividantur per maximum communem divisor, quoti sunt quadrato-quadrati. If similar plano-plane numbers bcdfgggg, bcdfhhhh are divided by their greatest commmon divisor, the quotients are square-squares.

add_6783_f009 9 17 JS Mar 28, 2012 Calculation of $ \sqrt{fg + bd} $. This is an algebraic version of the problem posed in Euclid X.59 , to find the square root (or side) of a sixth binome. The same problem was also worked on Add MS 6783 f. 7 , but $ (fg + bd) $ there has been replaced by $ cd $ here. Harriot's method, following Euclid, is to construct the square shown in the second diagram, in which the area of squares 1 + 3 represents $ \sqrt{cd} $ and the area of rectangles 2 + 2 represent $ fg $ (so each is of area $ \sqrt{\frac{fg}{4}} $. The side of square 1 is denoted by $ a $. It is clear from simple geometry that area 1 : area 2 = area 2 : area 3, so Harriot can write down three proportional terms $ a $, $ \sqrt{\frac{fg}{4}} $, $ \sqrt{cd} - a $. Thus $ \frac{fg}{4} = \sqrt{cdaa} - aa $, leading to a quadratic equation in $ a $. Harriot solves this equation by completing the square, giving him two possible values for $ a $. The side of the whole square is $ \sqrt{a} + \sqrt{\sqrt{cd} - a} $. Using either of his values for $ a $, he obtains the expression seen next to the words ‘Ergo Radix'. Squaring this expression gives him, as required, $ \sqrt{cd} + \sqrt{fg} $, the area of the whole square. He also observes that the sum of the roots gives him $ \sqrt{cd} $. b.9.) Radicum extractio. Extraction of roots

add_6783_f044v 44v 88 JS Mar 28, 2012 The table at the top right shows the numbers of Pascal's triangle set out in their simplest form. The table at the top left shows the same numbers written as fractions, thus $ \frac{456}{123} $ on the diagonal is to be read as $ \frac{4 \times 5 \times 6}{1 \times 2 \times 3} = 20 $, and similarly for all the rest. The third table displays the same numbers in a different arrangement, and suggests how they arise in the study of combinations. Thus the first margin note is $ \frac{n}{n} $, that is, the number of ways of choosing $ n $ objects from $ n $. This is always 1, which appears repeatedly along the lowest diagonal. The second margin note is $ \frac{n}{1} $, the number of ways of choosing 1 object from $ n $. The fractions $ \frac{n}{1} $ are seen along the second diagonal. The third margin note is $ \frac{n(n - 1)}{1 \times 2} $, the number of ways of choosing 2 objects from $ n $. The fractions $ \frac{n(n - 1)}{1 \times 2} $ are seen along the third diagonal. The fourth margin note is $ \frac{n(n - 1)(n - 2)}{1 \times 2 \times 3} $, the number of ways of choosing 3 objects from $ n $. The fractions $ \frac{n(n - 1)(n - 2)}{1 \times 2 \times 3} $ are seen along the fourth diagonal. These rules were known to Harriot from his study of Girolamo Cardano, Opus novum de proportionibus (Cardano 1570) , propositions 137 and 170 (see Add MS 6782 f. 44 ). The fourth table displays the numbers in the same layout as the third table, but now explicitly calculated. The numbers 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, ... below it are the sums for each column. A note on the right observes that the sum for each column is twice that of the preceding one. This sheet continues with third and fourth notations for triangular numbers on Add MS 6782 f. 330 . Elementa triangularium The elements of triangular numbers

add_6783_f064v 64v 128 JS Jan 26, 2013 Nota. Operatio pro eductione lateris maioris aliquando secundum partem est similis pro eductione lateris minoris. nimirum si utraque latera consentiant in primis figuris. ut si latus minus sit 23. maius 24. Ita si minus 343. maius 347. et sic de cæteris. Note. The operation for extracting the greater root is sometimes similar in the second part to the extraction of the smaller; clearly if both roots agree in the first figures, as when the smaller root is 23, the greater 24. Thus if the smaller is 343, the greater 347, and so on for others.

add_6783_f072 72 143 JS May 4, 2012 Against two of the equations on this page there are references to Stevin. These equations, $ 40 = - 6a + aaa $ and $ 20 = + 6a + aaa $ were treated by Stevin in L'arithmétique ... aussi l'algebre (Stevin 1585a) in his discussion of cubic equation without a square term (Problem LXIX). These equations were Stevin's first and second cases, treated at length on pages 305 to 311 and 311 to 314 respectively. Although Stevin gave the roots of each equation in the cube root form that Harriot gives here, he did not reduce them to their real equivalents. Thus, even though he observed that 4 is a root of the first equation, he did not explicitly identify $ \sqrt[3]{20 + \sqrt{392}} + \sqrt[3]{20 - \sqrt{392}} $ with 4. Harriot's work is continued on the next few sheets, Add MS 6783 f. 73 , f. 73 , f. 73 . See also Add MS 6786 f. 401 , where he calculates $ \sqrt[3]{20 + \sqrt{392}} + \sqrt[3]{20 - \sqrt{392}} $ arithmetically. add_6783_f098 98 195 JS Apr 28, 2012 This page is the first of a 29-page section on cubic equations. For a note on the tranlsation of 'genera', 'species', 'differentia', see Add MS 6783 f. 99 . The upper left part of this page shows all possible combinations of positive and negative terms in linear, quadratic, cubic, quartic, and quintic equations. The upper right half of the page contains a more sophisticated table, where the possibility of null terms is also taken into account. The box containing the figure 4, for instance, tallies the cases of cubic equation, excluding cases where all terms are negative. Thus, there is just 1 case of cubic equation with only a cube term; there are 3 cases with a cube and linear term; there are 3 cases with a cube and square term; and there are 7 cases with a cube, square, and linear term. These cases are listed explicitly on the following page, Add MS 6783 f. 99 . The table in the lower half of the page collects and summarizes this information. Thus the total number of cubics, under the heading (3), is $ 1 \times 1 + 2 \times 3 + 1 \times 7 = 14 $. Harriot also notes the totals, if cases where all the terms are negative are also counted. For some drafts and rough versions of this page, see Add MS 6783 f. 406v , f. 409v , f. 404 . e.1.) De resolutione æquationum per reductione On the solution of equations by reduction

add_6783_f102 102 203 JS Apr 28, 2012 Here Harriot investigates the equation $ 2ccc = aaa + 3bba $. From the identity proved on the previous page, Add MS 6783 f. 101 , he knows that a solution is $ q - r $, where $ qr = bb $ and $ qqq - rrr = 2ccc $. add_6783_f106 106 211 JS Apr 28, 2012 Here Harriot examines three possible cases of the equation $ 2ccc = - 3bba + aaa $, when $ c > b $, $ c \lt b $, $ c = b $. He calls these hyperbolic, elliptic, and parabolic, respectively. (For a page where Harriot experimented with other names for these forms, see Add MS 6784 f. 416 .) When $ c > b $, the equation has just one real root, given by the solution formula that Harriot has derived in sheets e.4, e.6, e.7, e.7.2 (Add MS 6783 f. 101 , f. 103 , f. 104 , f. 105 ). When $ c = b $, the equation has the double root $ a = - b $ and the single root $ a = 2b $. When $ c \lt b $, the equation has three distinct real roots, one positive and two negative; this is the 'impossible' case where the solution formula appears to give imaginary roots. However, Harriot has already shown in sheet d.4 (Add MS 6783 f. 180 ) that such equations have a real positive root. Now Harriot wishes to show that, conversely, the canonical forms derived in d.4 and e.4 do in fact have the defining properties of hyperbolic, elliptic, or parabolic equations. To do this, he makes use of two simple lemmas proved on the back of this page (add MS 6783, f. 106v). The canonical equation derived in e.4 was $ aaa - 3qra = rrr + qqq $. To show that this equation is hyperbolic, Harriot needs to prove that $ (\frac{qqq + rrr}{2})^2 > (qr)^3 $; this he is able to do using his two lemmas. The elliptic and parabolic cases are proved in sheet e.9, that is, Add MS 6783 f. 107 . e.8.) De resolutione æquationum per reductione On the solution of equations by reduction
add_6783_f106 106 211 JS Apr 28, 2012 e.8.) De resolutione æquationum per reductione On the solution of equations by reduction De tribus casibus antecendentis æquationis adventitæ Videlicet: On the three preceding case of the equation in question, namely:

add_6783_f107 107 213 JS Apr 28, 2012 The canonical equation derived in d.4 (Add MS 6783 f. 180 ) was $ aaa - qqa - qra - rra = qqr + qrr $. add_6783_f108 108 215 JS Apr 28, 2012 Up to now, Harriot has attempted to solve the equation $ 2ccc = - 3bba + aaa $ using the canonical form derived on e.4 (Add MS 6783, 101). Now he tries using an alternative form, derived on d.4 (Add MS 6783 f. 180 ). He must therefore set $ qq + qr + rr = 3bb $ and $ qqr + qrr = 2ccc $. Unfortunately, attempting to solve these simultaneously only brings him back to the original equation, except that the sign of the unknown quantity is now reversed; Harriot calls this the conjugate equation (see Add MS 6783 f. 180 ). He then tries using a second canonical form derived in d.4, but again is forced back to the original equation. He concludes from this that the elliptic case can only be solved by means of its conjugate, or else by the 'general way', that is, by Viète's numerical method. e.10.) add_6783_f110 110 219 JS Apr 28, 2012 Here Harriot turns to equations of the form $ 2ccc = + 3bba - aaa $. These are the 'avulsed equations' treated numerically in Section c . Such equations may have either two positive roots or none. Harriot begins with a canonical form derived in sheet d.3 (Add MS 6783 f. 181 ) for an equaion with two positive roots. He must therefore set $ qq + qr + rr = 3bb $ and $ qqr + qrr = 2ccc $. However, this simply brings him back to the origina equaton. He therefore tries another canon, from d.4 (Add MS 6783 f. 180 ), which requires him to set $ qq - qr + rr = 3bb $ and $ qqr - qrr = 2ccc $. This brings him back to the conjugate of the original equation. He therefore concludes, as on sheet e.10 (Add MS 6783 f. 108 ) that the given equation can only be solved by means of its conjugate, or else by Viète's numerical method. e.12.) add_6783_f112 112 223 JS Apr 28, 2012 As on sheet e.13 (Add MS 6783 f. 111 ) Harriot shows how the roots $ q $ and $ r $ of an equation of the form $ ggh = dfa - aaa $ can be determined from a known root $ x $ of the conjugate equation $ aaa - dfa = ggh $. His second method uses the second canonical form from d.4 (Add MS 6783 f. 180 ). His third method uses straightforward algebraic manipulation to arrive at the same result. At the end of the sheet is a summary of what has been treated so far in Section e: the three equations $ ggh = + dfa + aaa $, $ ggh = - dfa + aaa $, and $ ggh = + dfa - aaa $, but not linear or quadratic equations, which Harriot regards as already sufficently well understood. In the remainder of this section, he will show how to reduce any other cubic equation to one of these three types, by removing the square term. This is the 'reduction' that appears in the title throughout this section. e.14.) De resolutione æquationum per reductione On the solution of equations by reduction

add_6783_f113 113 225 JS Apr 29, 2012 This is the first page of a 7-page section on removing the cube term from a quartic equation; this is the 'reduction' that appears in the headings throughout Section f. Harriot's friend and colleague Nathaniel Torporley later denoted this subsection by the letter α, see: (Stedall 2003) , 247–258, and (section α) ). It is not self-contained, since the pagination (here 1 to 7) later continues into section γ (8 to 19), see: (section γ) ), but it is convenient to treat these first seven pages together. There is also another version of it, for which Torporley used the letter β, see: (section β) . This first page shows the removal of the cube term from the quartic equations $ xxxz = \pm 4raaa + aaaa $, using the substitution $ a = \pm e \mp r $. Harriot then solves the resulting equation for $ e $, either by inspection or by the methods shown in subsection δ (see Add MS 6783 f. 137 ). This gives him the two real roots of the original equation. (The other two are imaginary.) f. De resolutione æquationum per reductionem. (1. On the solution of equations by reduction.

add_6783_f122 122 243 If there be three magnitudes proportionall of which the first is the greatest: The square of the first, is æquall to the oblonge made of the difference of the first & the second; & the compounded of all these, together with the oblonge of the second & last.
add_6783_f122 122 243 Let the three lines $ ab $, $ bc $, & $ cd $ represent the three magnitudes in continuall proportion. From the poynt $ b $ & at right angles to the line $ ad $ let there be raysed a perpendicular $ bg $ æquall to $ bc $. And $ gb $ draw out to $ h $ so that $ gh $ be æquall to $ ab $. By the poynt $ h $ let the line $ ip $ be drawne parallell to $ ad $. And by the poynt $ g $ the line $ kq $ parallell also to $ ad $. Let $ iak $, $ hbg $, $ nco $, & $ pdq $, with $ xy $ & $ ut $ be also parallelles. Then the figure $ ihgk $ is a square, & also $ bcog $. $ ia $ or $ hb $ is the difference betweene $ ab $ & $ bg $ or $ bc $.
add_6783_f122 122 243 Now I say that the oblong $ id $ together with $ cq $ is æquall to the square $ ig $. The oblong $ ho $, is æquall to the oblong $ ag $, because $ gh $ & $ gk $; $ hn $ & $ ak $ are æquall.
add_6783_f122 122 243 Then is to be proved that $ nd $ is æquall to $ to $.
add_6783_f122 122 243 $ cd $ that is $ bt $ detracted from $ bc $ there remayneth $ tc $. & $ bc $ that is $ oc $ from $ on $ which is all one with $ ab $, there remayneth $ cn $. Therefore by the 19th of the 5th, $ tc $ to $ cn $ is as $ dc $ to $ co $ & therefore alternately as $ tc $ to $ cd $ so $ nc $ to $ co $. Therefour (by the 17th of the 6th or the 14th of the same) the oblongum $ nd $ is æquall to $ to $.
add_6783_f122 122 243 Then it is manifest that the oblong $ cq $ is æquall to $ bu $; & therefour the oblong $ nq $ æquall to the square $ bo $ & therefore the figure $ hdo $ æquall to the figure $ ag $. Unto both put the figure $ ib $. Therefour the square $ ig $. is æquall to the oblong $ id $ & $ do $; which was required to be proved.
add_6783_f122 122 243 In like manner if there be four proportionalls, as let the fourth be $ de $ the square $ ig $ is æquall to the oblong $ ie $ & $ ds $. Make $ c\alpha $ æquall to $ de $ then as before $ \alpha d $ wilbe to $ de $ as $ pd $ to $ dq $ & therfour the oblong $ pe $ æquall to $ \alpha q $, & the oblonge $ c\beta $ to $ ds $; Therefour is before the oblongs $ id $ & $ do $ were æquall to the square $ ig $; now also the oblongs $ ie $ & $ eg $ which is æquall to $ id $ & $ do $ must be also æquall. in like manner is the processe if there were never so many proportionalls or infinite &c.
add_6783_f122 122 243 Hereby it followeth.

add_6783_f123 123 245 To give two infinite progressions, of which one to be increasing & the other decreasing, that the totall summes may be æquall. although the nomber of be infinite, the last terms of both must be a quantity & finite.
add_6783_f123 123 245 To get the somme of an infinite progression is easy; but of a finite is to to be done thus besides other wayes; but this way will prove in many cases when others will not, especially in bynomialles.
add_6783_f123 123 245 The finite progression understand to runne infinite & get the summe: Then when the finite progression do end, get 2 or 3 nombers more in progression & from thence get the summe of the infinite ; the difference betwixt these summes of the two infinites is the summe of the finite progression.

add_6783_f135 135 269 JS Apr 29, 2012 As in Add MS 6783 f. 137 and f. 138 , the equations on this page are solved by completing a square. Harriot does so by adding a quantity $ eeaa + \frac{eeee}{4} $ to each side of $ aaaa = \mp2ccda + xxxz $. The condition for the right-hand side to be a perfect square is that $ ee(\frac{eeee}{4} + xxxz) = (ccd)(ccd) $. This gives him a cubic equation for $ e $, which in principle can be solved by the methods demonstrated in Section e. This is the standard method already taught by Cardano, Bombelli, Stevin, and Viète for solving quartic equations. f. De resolutione æquationum per reductionem. On the solution of equations by reduction.

add_6783_f137 137 273 JS Apr 29, 2012 In a set of sheets lettered 'e' (Add MS 6783 (Section e) ) Harriot gave a comprehensive treatment of cubic equations. In a similar set of sheets lettered 'f' he did the same for quartic equations (Section f) . Because there are many more cases of quartic to deal with, the sheets are more numerous, and are more widely dispersed amongst the mansucripts. After Harriot's death, his colleague Nathaniel Torporley allocated Greek letters to certain subsections of Section f, and we have followed that convention here. For further details of Torporley's notes on these pages, see (Stedall 2003) , 17–26. This is the first page of the 8-page section to which Torporley gave the letter δ (section δ) ). The reason for putting this section first in the present scheme is that it treats quartic equations with no cube term, which can therefore be solved by 'completing the square'. The aim of all the other sections is to reduce more general quartic equations to this type so that they can be solved in the same way. This preserves an analogy with Harriot's treatment of cubics, where cubics with no square term were treated first, and all other case were then reduced to this special type. f. add_6783_f156v 156v 312 JS Nov 14, 2012 Blank page
add_6783_f157 157 313 JS Apr 29, 2012 On this page, for the first time in this section, Harriot solves a quartic equation not only for two real roots but also for two imaginary roots. He states that these are derived from the rules given on sheet e.13 (Add MS 6783, f.111). There, and on e.14 (Add MS 6783 f. 112 ) he showed how to derive two roots of an equation from a single known root of its conjugate. More specifically, given the single positive root $ x $ of an equation of the form $ aaa - dfa = ggh $, Harriot derived a quadratic equation for the two roots of the conjugate equation $ dfa - aaa = ggh $. That quadratic equation was $ ee - xe = df - xx $, with roots $ e = \frac{e}{2} \pm \sqrt{df - \frac{3xx}{4}} $. On this page Harriot wants to solve the equation $ 20 = 11e - eee $. The conjugate equation is $ eee - 11e = 20 $, which has the single positive root $ e = 4 $ (as can be seen by inspection). Harriot therefore now has $ x = 4 $ and $ df = 11 $. Thus his quadratic equation is $ ee - 4e + 5 = 0 $, with roots $ e = 2 \pm \sqrt{-1} $. Previously he might have rejected these roots as 'impossible' (see sheet e.16, Add MS 6783, f. 197, but on this page he accepts them, and follows the working to its conclusion, giving him all four roots of the original equation. He notes that roots of the kind he has found here are given by the canonical form $ (a - b)(a - c)(aa + df) $ shown in sheet d.13.2 (Ad MS 6783 f. 156 ), a sheet that has been inserted immediately before the present page. f. add_6783_f168 168 335 JS Apr 28, 2012 Another collection of canonical equations, as on Add MS 6783 f. 170 and f. 169 , but now for equations with as many positive roots as the degree of the equation. The last of these, an equation of fifth degree, has not been derived in the pages of Section d but can be written down by analogy; see also Add MS 6784 f. 427 . Viète, at the end of his De recognitione et emendatione æquationum, tractatus duo (Viète 1615) , offered several collections of equations and their solutions. In general Harriot's collections are different from Viète's. This page, however, contains the same equations as Viète's fourth and final collection, the 'Collectio quarta'. I would argue that Viète derived his equations by his method of syncrisis (see Stedall 2011, 24–27 ), which is quite different from Harriot's multiplication of factors. d.16.) add_6783_f177 177 353 JS Apr 28, 2012 On this page Harriot explores the multiplications $ (a - b)( a - c)(a - d)( a - f) = 0 $ and $ (a - b)( a - c)(a - d)( a + f) = 0 $. In the latter case, he demonstrates the conditions required for the terms in $ aaa $, $ aa $, or $ a $ to vanish, and finds the resulting form of the coefficients in terms of the three positive roots $ b $, $ c $, and $ d $. From this it is easy for him to see the close relationship between the equations in Add MS 6783 f. 181 and f. 180 : the positive root in the latter is the sum of the positive roots in the former. In modern terms we would say that the positive roots in one equation are the negative roots in the other. Harriot calls such pairs 'conjugate' or 'converse'. d.7.) add_6783_f180 180 359 JS Apr 28, 2012 On this page Harriot explores the multiplication $ (a + b)( a + c)(a - d) = 0 $. He states that $ d $ is the only (positive) roots of this equation but does not offer any justification. As in Add MS 6783 f. 181 , he demonstrates the conditions required for the term in $ aa $ to vanish, and finds the resulting form of the coefficients in terms of $ b $ and $ c $. From this it is easy for him to see the close relationship between the equations in Add MS 6783 f. 181 and f. 180 : the positive root in the latter is the sum of the positive roots in the former. In modern terms we would say that the positive roots in one equation are the negative roots in the other. Harriot calls such pairs 'conjugate' or 'converse'. d.4.) add_6783_f183 183 365 JS Apr 28, 2012 In this 21-page section (Section d), Harriot develops one of his most original ideas in algebra: the generation of polynomial equations from the multiplication of linear and quadratic factors. All previous treatments of quadratic, cubic, or quartic equations had been based on traditional ideas of proportion. Harriot broke decisively away from such a model, completely changing the way equations were perceived and studied. This was the one section of Harriot's work that was published after his death, edited by his friend Walter Warner as the Artis analyticae praxis (1631). Warner, however, seems not to have fully understood all of Harriot's working, and the version given in the Praxis is very different from the systematic treatment seen in the manuscripts. Further, Warner eliminated all negative or imaginary roots, leading later readers to assume that Harriot never handled them. That he did so is clear from the later pages in this section. The 'canoncial equations' in Section d are prototypes, generated from a given set of roots. Note that Harriot has already used these canonical equations in Section c (Add MS 6783 f. 417 to f. 400 ); see, for example, Add MS 6783 f. 417 , f (for quadratics), f. 415 , f. 414 , f. 411 , f. 410 , f. 409 , f. 408 (for cubics), f. 407 , f. 406 , f. 404 , f. 403 , f. 402 , f. 400 (for quartics). These are different from some other equations, also described as 'canonical', also to be found in Section c. For a page that shows both types, see Add MS 6782 f. 408 . There the first canonical form is of the kind derived here in Section d, for a cubic equation with no linear term, and with two positive roots $ b $ and $ c $. The second canonical form is used for numerical solution; in that case, $ b $ and $ c $ represent the first and second digits of the root. Thus $ b $ and $ c $ have entirely different interpretations in the two forms; fortunately, their specific meanings in any calculation are always clear from the context. The equations in Section c are all trinomial in form, with the highest power subtracted (torn away, or 'avulsed') from the second highest power. Such equations have either no positive roots or two of them. From his study of Viète's numerical method, Harriot was particularly interested in the latter case. His aim in Section d is to discover the conditions under which an equation with two positive roots reduces to trinomial form, and the nature of the resulting coefficients in terms of those two roots. Thus Sections c and d are very closely related, and there are several specific cross-references from one to the other. For further discussion see Stedall 2011 . As for other parts of Harriot's work on equations, algebraic manipulations and single words contained in them are not transcribed in this section. In this first page (d.1) Harriot sets out the multiplications he intends to explore, in modern notation $ (a - b) $, $ (a - b )(a - c) $, $ (a - b)(a + b) $, $ (a - b)(a - c)(a - d) $, and so on. After the trivial case $ a - b = 0 $, Harriot treats the multiplication $ (a - b)(a - c) = 0 $, arguing that $ b $ and $ c $ are both (positive) roots of this equation, but that there can be no other (positive) root $ d $, say. He then treats the multiplication $ (a - b)(a + c) $ in a similar way, arguing that in this case $ a = b $ is the only (positive) root. At this stage he is still concerned only with positive roots, though this will change later. d.1.) De generatione æquationum canonicarum On the generation of canonical equations

add_6783_f186 186 371 JS Apr 30, 2012 This page begins with the sixth and last of the equations given by Viète in De numerosa potestum resolutione, in the section entitled 'De ambiguitate cubi multipliciter adfecti' ('On ambiguity in cubic equations with multiple terms'), following Problem 18 (Viète 1600b) . Harriot then goes on to discuss some of the 'precepts' given by Viète, with his own corrections to them. Viète's first equation was (in modern notation) $ x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x = 6 $. Harriot gives this in the form $ aaa - 6aa + 11a = 6 $. Viète claimed that this has three real and distinct roots (namely, 1, 2, and 3) because $ 3 \times \left(\frac{6}{3}\right)^2 > 11 $. In more general terms, for an equation $ x^3 - px^2 + qx - r = 0 $, this condition may be written $ 3\left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^2 > q $ (condition (i)). It is true that if all the roots are real, this condition will be satisfied. If the roots are $ b $, $ c $, $ d $, for instance, then it is equivalent to $ 3\left(\frac{b + c + d}{3}\right)^2 > bc + cd + db $, precisely the inequality Harriot proves on the next page, sheet e.28 (Add MS 6783 f. 185 ), Lemma 2. However, although this condition is necessary for the equation to have three real roots, it is not sufficient. To demonstrate this, Harriot adjoins a second example, $ aaa - 6aa + 11a = 12 $, where the condition is again satisfied, but the equation has only one real root, $ a = 4 $. Harriot claims that a further condition is necessary for three (real) roots, namely, $ \left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^3 > r $ (condition (ii)). This is equivalent to $ \left(\frac{b + c + d}{3}\right)^3 > bcd $, the inequality that he proves on sheet e.29 (Add MS 6783 f. 184 ), Lemma 3. Harriot's first equation satisfies condition (ii), but the second does not. However, as before, he has only shown that condition (ii) is necessary for three real roots, not that it is sufficient. Viète made a further claim: that the roots of the first equation (namely, 1, 2, and 3) are equally spaced because $ 6 + 2 \times \left(\frac{6}{3}\right)^3 = 11 \times \frac{6}{3} $. In more general terms, using the notation above, $ r + 2\left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^3 = \frac{p}{3}q $. Viète did not justify this statement but it is not difficult to check that this condition must indeed hold if the roots are equally spaced. Harriot next turns to examples when condition (i) becomes an equality, that is, $ 3\left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^2 = r $ (condition (i')). Viète claimed that this leads to three equal roots, as in the equation (in modern notation) $ x^3 - 6x^2 + 12x = 8 $, with roots 2, 2, 2. Harriot writes this in the form $ aaa - 6aa + 12a = 8 $. Harriot again shows that although Viète's condition is necessary for three real roots, it is not sufficient. He does so by adjoining a second example, $ aaa - 6aa + 11a = 9 $, where condition (i') is satisfied, but the equation has only one real root, $ a = 3 $. Harriot claims that a further condition is necessary for three (real) roots, namely (in the above notation), $ r + 2\left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^3 = \frac{p}{3}q $ (condition (ii')). This is precisely Viète's condition for equally spaced roots, but Harriot offers no justification for his statement. His first equation satisfies condition (ii'), but his second does not. Harriot's third condition, in the above notation $ 3\left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^2 \le q $, is the negation of condition (i); when this holds there can be only one real root, as in his example, $ aaa - 6aa + 13a = 8 $. Harrot's fourth condition, in the above notation $ \left(\frac{p}{3}\right)^3 \le r $, is the negation of condition (ii); when this holds there can be only one real root, as in his two examples, $ aaa - 6aa + 11a = 12 $ and $ aaa - 6aa + 12a = 9 $. e.27.) add_6783_f187 187 373 JS Apr 30, 2012 The equations on this page are the first five of those discussed by Viète in De numerosa potestum resolutione, in a section entitled 'De ambiguitate cubi multipliciter adfecti' ('On ambiguity in cubic equations with multiple terms'), following Problem 18 (Viète 1600b) . add_6783_f204 204 407 JS Apr 28, 2012 Harriot continues his exploration of the equation generated by the multiplication $ (a - b)( a - c )( a - d )( a + f ) = 0 $. Here he invesitgates the conditions required for two terms, in $ aa $ and $ aad $ to vanish simultaneously. This leads him to values of $ d $ and $ f $ which are clearly imaginary or, in the language of Harriot's time, 'impossible' (since $ b $ and $ c $ are both supposed positive). This is a contradiction since $ d $ was supposed positive. Harriot does not seem concerned about this, however, and goes on to add and multiply $ d $ and $ f $ without comment. When Warner came to edit these pages in the Artis analyticae praxis (1631), he was troubled by these manipulations and omitted them, stating that they were 'not clear'. The contradiction lingers in the fact that Harriot started from an equation with three positive roots, but ends up with an equation with only two, even though his procedures have done nothing to change the roots themselves. d.7.2
add_6783_f204 204 407 JS Apr 28, 2012 d.7.2 Tollere, ($ aa $ et $ aaa $) To remove $ aa $ and $ aaa $.

add_6783_f232 232 463 JS May 3, 2012 This sheet refers to Stevin's L'arithmétique ... aussi l'algebre (Stevin 1585a) . On page 308, Stevin wrote the following, about equations he described as 'imparfaicte' (imperfect). These are equations with three real roots, but where the solution formula appears at first sight to give imaginary roots. Stevin went on to give a solution of 1(3) = 30(1) + 36 (in modern notation $ x^3 = 30x + 36 $) involving $ \sqrt{-676} $. He also observed that 6 is a solution. Harriot worked on the same equation, written as $ aaa - 30a = 36 $. For the 1579 edition of Bombelli's L'algebra see (Bombelli 1579)

add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 This is the first of a set of 10 pages of notes on Viète's Effectionum geometricarum canonica recensio (Viète 1593b, Props 5, 6) , which supplies 20 Euclidean constructions of lines in given arithmetical or proportional relationships. Propositions 1 and 2, for example, simply show how to add or subtract one line to or from another. Proposition 3 gives the standard Euclidean construction for three lines in geometric proportion, Proposition VI.13 . On this page, Harriot gives his own versions of Propositions 5 and 6. Harriot, following Viète, describes the first as the work of multiplication, and the second as the work of division. This can be seen more clearly from Harriot's algebraic treatment than from Viète's geometric construction. This, in Proposition 5, the square of $ d $ (the line to be constructed) represents the product of the given lines $ b $ and $ c $. In Proposition 6, the line $ c $ (to be constructed) represents the quotient $ \frac{dd}{b} $ of the given quantites $ dd $ and $ b $. a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions
add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions Invenire, quadratum $ = bc $ Opus multiplicationis.) To find a square equal to $ bc $ (the work of multiplication)
add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions fiat periferia cuius diameter $ b + c $ fit $ fd $ perpendicularis, signata, $ d $ Construct the circumference whose diameter is $ b + c $. Let $ fd $ be the perpendicular, denoted $ d $.
add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions Aliter sit $ aa = bc $ et quæritur. $ a $ ergo: $ b , a : a , c $. Igitur Inter $ b $ et $ c $ inveniatur media proportionalis, et signetur $ d $. Another way. Let $ aa = bc $, and $ a $ is sought, that is, $ b : a = a : c $. Therefore between $ b $ and $ c $ there may be found a mean proportional, denoted by $ d $.
add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions Invenire, planum $ = dd $ cuius unum latus datum, nempe, $ b $. Opus applicationis.) fiat $ bf = b $. et $ df = d $. perpendicularis. agatur $ bd $. et secetur bisariam in $ g $. sit $ ga $, perpendicularis, quæ secabit $ bf $ lineam in $ a $. centro $ a $. intervallo $ ab $, fiat periferia. quæ secabit $ bf $ productam in $ c $ puncto. notetur $ fc $ $ c $. To find a plane equal to $ dd $, of which one side is given, namely $ b $ (the work of division). Construct $ bf = b $, and $ df = d $, the perpendicular. Join $ bd $ and let it be bisected at $ g $. Let $ ga $ be a perpendicular, which cuts the line $ bf $ produced at $ a $. With centre $ a $ and radius $ ab $ construct the circumference, which cuts $ bf $ produced at the point $ c $. It may be observed that $ fc $ is $ c $.
add_6783_f233 233 465 JS Jul 16, 2012 a.) Effectiones geometricæ Geometrical constructions Aliter sit $ be = dd $ et quæritur. $ e $ ergo: $ b , d : d , e $. Igitur inveniatur tertia proportio- nalis et signetur $ d $. Another way. Let $ be = dd $, and $ e $ is sought, that is $ b : d = d : e $. Therefore there may be found a third proportional, denoted by $ d $.

add_6783_f236 236 471 JS Jul 16, 2012 On this page, Harriot works on Propositions 9 and 10 from Viète's Effectionum geometricarum canonica recensio (Viète 1593b, Props 9, 10) . In both of these propositions, Viète showed how the standard construction for three proportionals can lead to the given equation. Harriot works the other way round: beginning from an equation, he gives a construction that represents the same relationship geometrically. This is what he means by 'effectio æquationis' or 'the construction of an equation'. d.) Effectiones geometricae Geometric constructions

The upper half of the page, below the number '5.)', contains several versions of a formula for fifth binomes, the simplest of which, marked 'melius' (best), is $ \sqrt{bb + cd} + b $. add_6783_f356 356 711 JS Nov 14, 2012 Rough work
add_6783_f356v 356v 712 JS May 10, 2012 This is the first of a set of 14 numbered pages on binomes. The six types of binome are defined in Euclid's Elements in Book X; Definitions II , in the following way. These definitions may be written in modern notation as follows. Binome 1: a binome of the form $ m + \sqrt{n} $ with $ m > \sqrt{n} $, and $ m^2 = n + k $ where $ \frac{m}{\sqrt{k}} $ is rational; for example $ 7 + \sqrt{48} $. Binome 2: a binome of the form $ \sqrt{m} + n $ with $ \sqrt{m} > n $, and $ m = n^2 + k $ where $ \frac{\sqrt{m}}{\sqrt{k}} $ is rational; for example $ \sqrt{12} + 3 $. Binome 3: a binome of the form$ \sqrt{m} + \sqrt{n} $ with $ \sqrt{m} > \sqrt{n} $, and $ m = n + k $ where $ \frac{\sqrt{m}}{\sqrt{k}} $ is rational; for example $ \sqrt{8} + \sqrt{6} $. Binome 4: a binome of the form $ m + \sqrt{n} $ with $ m > \sqrt{n} $, and $ m^2 = n + k $ where $ \frac{m}{\sqrt{k}} $ is non-rational; for example $ 2 + \sqrt{2} $. Binome 5: a binome of the form $ \sqrt{m} + n $ with $ \sqrt{m} > n $, and $ m = n^2 + k $ where $ \frac{\sqrt{m}}{\sqrt{k}} $ is non-rational; for example $ \sqrt{2} + 1 $. Binome 6: a binome of the form $ \sqrt{m} + \sqrt{n} $ with $ \sqrt{m} > \sqrt{n} $, and $ m = n + k $ where $ \frac{\sqrt{m}}{\sqrt{k}} $ is non-rational; for example $ \sqrt{3} + \sqrt{2} $. Harriot made two further distinctions for binomes of the fifth and sixth kind according to whether $ k $ is itself a square (type i) or not (type ii). Harriot also investigated two further kinds of irrational quantities defined by Euclid: first and second bimedials. These are defined in Euclid X.37 and X.38. On this page, Harriot derives general formulae for binomes of the first and second kind. Three lines after the word 'Aliter' on the right is his formula for first binomes: $ b + \sqrt{bb - dd} $. On the lower half of the page, below the number 2.) is his formula for second binomes: $ \sqrt{\frac{bbff}{bb - dd} + f} $. In each case he gives several numerical exmples. 1.) add_6783_f359 359 717 JS Jan 14, 2013 Rough work on square roots of binomes
add_6783_f359v 359v 718 JS Jan 26, 2013 A table of square roots of binomes. Down the left hand side of the table Harriot has listed eight kinds of binomes of the first kind, that is, of the form $ a + \sqrt{b} $ where $ a^2 > b $. They are distinguished by the fact that their square roots are binomes of the first, second, third, fourth, fifth, or sixth kind. Note that Harriot defines two classes of binome of the fifth kind and of the sixth kind. In each case, those in the first class are those special cases where the difference between the square of the two terms is itself a square. Harriot observes that 'Euclides non distinxit', that is, that Euclid does not make this distinction. The third column shows the square roots of the square roots, that is, the fourth roots of the original quantity. The fourth and final column gives the names assigned by Euclid to these fourth roots. At the bottom of the page are some further quantities 'omitted by Euclid'.
add_6783_f359v 359v 718 JS Jan 26, 2013 Rationalis: Aut, Rationale. 6. Of a rational or, from a rational 6.

add_6783_f359v 359v 718 JS Jan 26, 2013 cuius radix $ \sqrt{\sqrt{6}} $. whose root is $ \sqrt[4]{6} $.

add_6783_f362v 362v 724 JS Mar 28, 2012 Square roots of binomes by the rule given on Add MS 6788 f. 15 (and elsewhere). The first section demonstrates that the square root of a third binome is the root of a third binome plus the root of a third apotome. The third section gives the square root of a fourth binome. The fourth section demonstrates that the square root of a fifth binome of the second kind is the root of a sixth binome of the first kind plus the root of a sixth apotome of the first kind. The fifth section demonstrates that the square root of a fifth binome of the first kind is the root of a fifth binome of the first kind plus the root a fifth apotome of the first kind. The sixth section demonstrates that the square root of a sixth binome of the first kind is the root of a fifth binome of the second kind plus the root a fifth apotome of the second kind, and that the square root of a sixth binome of the second kind is the root of a sixth binome of the second kind plus the root a sixth apotome of the second kind. The seventh section demonstrates again that the square root of a sixth binome of the first kind is the root of a fifth binome of the second kind plus the root a fifth apotome of the second kind, and that the square root of a sixth binome of the second kind is the root of a sixth binome of the second kind plus the root a sixth apotome of the second kind. For Harriot's two kinds of fifth and sixth binomes, see Add MS 6784, 216.

add_6783_f395v 395v 790 JS Mar 28, 2012 This folio provides a canon, or rule, for finding the cube root of a quantity $ d + f $. Using the fundamental property established in the first line, the first denominator of the canon can be rewritten as the cube root of $ 2bbb + 6bcc + 3((b + c)(bb - cc) + (b - c)(bb - cc)) $ $ = 2bbb + 6bcc + 6b(bb - cc) $ $ = 8bbb $. Similarly, the second denominator yields $ 8ccc $. Thus taking cube roots and dividing by 2 yields $ b + c $, as required. A numerical example is worked at the bottom of the page.
